[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So I\'d like to introduce you to somebody. This is Walter. He\'s my workshop automated laser tracking and engagement robot. And I built Walter because I\'ve a lot of top secret projects that I want to share with you soon, but I want to make sure that no'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one can come in and take a peek before they\'re ready to share. So instead of buying a off-the-shelf Wi-Fi camera like any normal person would, I decided to build a robot from the ground up using custom components to keep an eye on my'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workshop when I\'m away and building in a few skills that I\'m going to reveal throughout the course of this video. So to get things started, I had to design everything in my go-to computer-aided design software Fusion [music] 360. The'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'design of Walter all centered around this lazy Susan bearing that was going to be the primary mechanism to allow Walter to seamlessly [music] pan to look all the way around my workshop. I also'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'knew I was going to want to control Walter from anywhere in the world, so central to Walter\'s electrical design &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; is a Raspberry Pi that will connect to an Arduino which then in turn uses stepper motor drivers to control'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Walter\'s pan and [music] tilt axis. However, before I could jump into assembling everything, I always [music] want to check to make sure that the electronics are working as expected. This saves me so much heartburn when I'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go to solder everything up on these proto [music] boards to make connections permanent, and I can also find little bugs in the system before things get harder to change later. In addition to a high-definition camera, I also wanted to have two high-intensity'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'floodlights and two lasers because well, lasers are awesome. To take things [music] a step further, I\'m going to give Walter the ability to listen to voice commands via a microphone as well as the ability to speak using this little USB speaker that'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I tore apart. And now I\'m almost 100% certain the way I\'m mounting this speaker and giving it no space behind it is incorrect, but it helped me save some space. To allow Walter to spin indefinitely on'

[01:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'his pan axis, I installed [music] what\'s called a slip ring connector which ensures a solid electrical connection while still enabling rotation. So Walter can just pan all the way around my workshop over and over and'

[02:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'never get tangled up in wires. So now that I had selected and tested all of these components, it was time to start putting Walter together starting with his base. This was the part of the little robot'

[02:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that would ultimately mount to the ceiling of my workshop to get the best possible view of the entire space. [music] This speaker assembly that I showed you before is going to be the primary tilting component [music] of Walter,'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which this face component, which contains Walter\'s camera, lasers, and lights will mount to and allow Walter to look up and down. Once I had Walter\'s face assembled, I'

[02:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'had to turn my attention back to assembling the base which proved to be surprisingly tricky [music] only because when I was designing this part of the robot, I didn\'t really think for how it was going to be assembled. So the order'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in which I put things together really mattered. Not only that, but I had to shim a lot of these little spacers using the washers that you saw there [music] to ensure that there was just enough clearance for things to rotate cleanly'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'while not scraping. So then to integrate the speaker assembly, which was the primary [music] tilt component of Walter with the base, which is the primary pan component, I have these little arm brackets that I'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'designed which also house limit switches so that Walter knows how far he can tilt up and down without stressing the motors by over rotating and pressing components'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'together too firmly. All of the pain that you see me going through with trying to assemble Walter really highlights the need for something called design for manufacturing. And all that means is that you not only design'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for the end result that you want to achieve [music] with your specific product, but you also design for how it\'s going to be put together making that easy so that you don\'t [music] run into the same issues that I did here. But once I did finally'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get Walter put together, things started looking pretty cool. Now that all the mechanical components were put together, I could turn my attention to soldering up all the electronics using this proto board and'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some really rough solder connections. Another pro tip here to call out is actually pay attention to the amount of [music] wiring you\'re going to need because I didn\'t in this case and it turned into a total rat\'s nest, but we'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still got things working. Before I connected the Raspberry Pi to give me real-time control of Walter, I first use a test script on the Arduino simply to run through the paces of moving the'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'motors and testing the limit switches. Here you can see how the limit switches work where Walter will rotate until he detects that a switch has been pressed and then rotate back the other way until the other limit switch has been pressed,'

[05:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thus establishing his range of motion. So now we could get into some of the cool stuff using our Raspberry Pi. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Instead of a script that ran over and over, I could now integrate an Android tablet with a gamepad style controller'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to control Walter in real time using a wireless connection. The hardest part here was just simply establishing a low latency connection that not only allowed me to control'

[05:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
